{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 14:37:25.169517", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting diagnosis report\nDate: (runtime)\nScope / summary\n- Network: enterprise hierarchical OSPF network with three core routers, two distribution routers (router_dist_1_1, router_dist_2_1), server-access router and server farm (10.200.0.0/24).\n- Purpose: determine whether there is any anomalous behavior, localize faulty device(s), and identify likely root cause(s).\n- High-level conclusion: The network is mostly functional, but traffic from the 10.1.1.0/24 edge (hosts behind router_dist_1_1) cannot reach the server farm subnet 10.200.0.0/24 because router_dist_1_1 lacks OSPF routes to the server network. Hosts behind router_dist_2_1 (10.2.x/24) can reach the servers normally.\n\nWhat I ran (commands / checks)\n- Collected global reachability summary (automated reachability matrix).\n- From two edge hosts I attempted pings to servers and load‑balancer (parallel ping tests).\n- Retrieved host_1_1_1_1 network configuration (ifconfig, ip addr, ip route).\n- Retrieved routing tables (vtysh show ip route) from:\n  - router_dist_1_1\n  - router_dist_2_1\n  - server_access_router\n  - router_core_1\n  - router_core_2\n\nKey findings (abnormal behavior)\n1) router_dist_1_1 is missing routes to the server farm (10.200.0.0/24) and other remote prefixes:\n   - router_dist_1_1 routing table shows only:\n     - 10.1.1.0/24 (direct)\n     - 172.16.0.6/31 (direct)\n   - It does NOT show an OSPF route to 10.200.0.0/24, nor the other 10.x/24 prefixes that should be carried by OSPF.\n\n2) Host-side symptom consistent with missing route:\n   - host_1_1_1_1 (10.1.1.12) default gateway: 10.1.1.1 (ip route shows \"default via 10.1.1.1\").\n   - A ping from host_1_1_1_1 to the DNS server 10.200.0.2 produced \"From 10.1.1.1 icmp_seq=n Destination Net Unreachable\". That is the default gateway (router_dist_1_1) indicating it has no route to the destination.\n\n3) Other distribution/core routers have proper OSPF routes to the server network:\n   - router_dist_2_1 shows OSPF learned routes including 10.200.0.0/24 via 172.16.0.10.\n   - server_access_router is directly connected to 10.200.0.0/24 and shows expected routes.\n   - router_core_1 and router_core_2 have OSPF routes to 10.200.0.0/24 via their respective next-hops.\n\n4) Reachability matrix and ping tests:\n   - Many hosts and servers can reach each other normally (no packet loss) — particularly hosts in 10.2.x networks can reach servers and DNS.\n   - Pings initiated from host_1_1_1_1 to server addresses initially timed out / returned unreachable from the gateway, consistent with missing route on router_dist_1_1.\n   - Pings from hosts behind router_dist_2_1 to web servers and DNS succeeded.\n\nLocalization: likely faulty device(s)\n- Primary device: router_dist_1_1\n  - Symptoms localize to this device because:\n    - It's the default gateway for the affected host subnet (10.1.1.0/24).\n    - Its routing table lacks the OSPF-learned prefixes to the server farm while other routers have them.\n    - It returned \"Destination Net Unreachable\" for traffic from its subnet toward 10.200.0.2.\n\nImpact / severity\n- Impacted scope: hosts in 10.1.1.0/24 (at least host_1_1_1_1 shown) cannot reach the server farm (10.200.0.0/24), so they cannot reach DNS, the load balancer, or backend web services.\n- Other subnets (10.2.x) can reach the servers — so impact is localized to the 10.1.1.0/24 area.\n- Severity: Medium for users in the affected subnet (loss of access to centralized services), low to overall network since other areas remain functional.\n\nEvidence (selected outputs)\n- host_1_1_1_1 network config:\n  - inet 10.1.1.12/24, default via 10.1.1.1\n- Ping from host_1_1_1_1 to 10.200.0.2:\n  - Response: \"From 10.1.1.1 icmp_seq=n Destination Net Unreachable\" (gateway denies/has no route)\n- router_dist_1_1 \"show ip route\":\n  - Only 10.1.1.0/24 and 172.16.0.6/31 appear; no 10.200.0.0/24 route.\n- router_dist_2_1 \"show ip route\":\n  - Has OSPF route \"10.200.0.0/24 via 172.16.0.10\" (learned).\n- server_access_router \"show ip route\":\n  - 10.200.0.0/24 is directly connected (br0).\n- Pings from hosts on 10.2.x networks to web servers and DNS succeeded (no loss), demonstrating the server network is reachable from other distribution/core paths.\n\nLikely root cause(s)\n- router_dist_1_1 is not learning OSPF routes for remote networks (including 10.200.0.0/24). Possible underlying causes (diagnostic hypotheses only):\n  - OSPF adjacency issues on router_dist_1_1 (adjacencies with core routers failed or are not established).\n  - router_dist_1_1 OSPF configuration missing the interfaces or area assignment that would allow it to receive LSAs.\n  - Filtering / route-policy / distribute-list on router_dist_1_1 preventing acceptance of external LSAs or specific prefixes.\n  - FRR process (OSPF daemon) not running or partially failed on router_dist_1_1 (not evident from routes alone).\n  - Interface-level problem limiting exchange of OSPF (e.g., the link toward the core is down, misconfigured, or in a different subnet).\n\nNotes / suggested next diagnostic checks (no remediation steps included)\n- On router_dist_1_1:\n  - show ip ospf neighbor (to verify adjacencies)\n  - show ip ospf database (to see what LSAs it has)\n  - check FRR ospfd process status (systemctl status frr / vtysh show running-config ospf)\n  - check interface status toward the core (ip addr / ip link show / ethtool)\n  - check for any route-filters / distribute-lists applied to OSPF or RIB\n- Compare OSPF neighbor/DB output between router_dist_1_1 and router_dist_2_1 to find differences.\n- If needed, capture logs from FRR/OSPF to see adjacency or LSA errors.\n\nClosing summary\n- The network is largely healthy, but there is a clear localized routing failure: router_dist_1_1 is not learning/advertising OSPF routes to the server farm (10.200.0.0/24). This explains the \"Destination Net Unreachable\" seen by hosts in 10.1.1.0/24. Other distribution and core routers have the correct OSPF routes and hosts behind them are unaffected. The next step is to inspect OSPF adjacency and FRR on router_dist_1_1 to determine why OSPF route exchange is not occurring (diagnostic checks listed above).", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 13582, "output_tokens": 3133, "total_tokens": 16715, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 12800}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 1408}}}
